[[File:Barranquilla,_el_mar_desde_las_Bocas_de_Cenizas-20050625.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Sunset in Bocas de Ceniza.]]

'''Bocas de Ceniza''' (Spanish for: ''Ash Mouths'') is the mouth of the [[Magdalena River]] in the [[Caribbean Sea]]. It owes its name to the dusky color ocean waters take to receive the river. At present, the river flows into the sea through an artificial canal built in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.puertodebarranquilla.com/?page_id%3D191 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407022117/http://www.puertodebarranquilla.com/?page_id=191 |archivedate=2016-04-07 |df= }}</ref>

==History==
Bocas de Ceniza was discovered by [[Rodrigo de Bastidas]] on 1 April 1501. In 1824 the river navigation steamships began, raising local interest in the use of Bocas de Ceniza. The railway construction between [[Barranquilla]] and [[Puerto Colombia]] in 1872 and the transfer of Aduana Nacional to Barranquilla increased the desire to enable the sector of Bocas de Ceniza for international maritime trade.

