{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox government agency |agency_name = Western Australian Planning Commission |type = Planning Authority |nativename = |nativename_a = |nativename_r = |logo = |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |picture = |picture_width = |picture_caption = |formed = 1955 |preceding1 = |superseding = |jurisdiction = [[Government of Western Australia]] |headquarters = |coordinates = <!--{{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}}--> |motto = |employees = |budget = |minister1_name = Eric Lumsden |minister1_pfo = WAPC Chairman |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = |agency_type = |parent_department = Department of Planning |parent_agency = |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |keydocument1 = |website = {{URL|planning.wa.gov.au}} |footnotes = |map = |map_width = |map_caption = }}
The '''Western Australian Planning Commission''' ('''WAPC''') is a statutory authority of the [[Government of Western Australia]] that exists to coordinate planning for future land use and transport needs. It describes itself as [[Western Australia]]'s "peak representative body of [[land-use planning]] and development".{{cn|date=June 2014}} Its main role is to coordinate the various government agencies and other stakeholders in large infrastructure projects, to ensure that consideration is given to all interests and needs, including environmental, economic and community interests. It operates within the purview of the [[Department of Planning]], which is responsible to the [[Minister for Planning (Western Australia)|Minister for Planning]].
==History== The commission was originally called the '''Metropolitan Regional Planning Authority''' (MRPA) when it was established with [[David Carr (Austrlian)|David Carr]] as the chief planner. Shortly after that time, in 1965 [[Paul Ritter]] became the first city planner for Perth.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://dspace.flinders.edu.au/dspace/bitstream/2328/653/1/49.pdf | title = Light and Shade | author = David Hutchison |magazine= Australian Book Review |date=March 2004 |page=49 | issn = 0155-2864 | accessdate = 2007-07-17 }}</ref>
===Timeline=== * 1955: Stephenson Hepburn report recommends a metropolitan region scheme, an ongoing regional improvement fund and an independent expert regional planning authority.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Stephenson, Gordon | author2=Hepburn, J. A. (John Alastair), 1915- | author3=Stephenson, Gordon, 1908-. Plan for the metropolitan region Perth and Fremantle Western Australia 1955 Atlas | author4=Western Australia. Town Planning Department | title=Plan for the metropolitan region, Perth and Fremantle, Western Australia, 1955 : a report prepared for the Government of Western Australia | publication-date=1955 | publisher=Government Printing Office | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/26249494 | accessdate=8 June 2014 }}</ref> * 1963: [[Perth Metropolitan Region Scheme|Metropolitan Region Scheme]] adopted by the [[Parliament of Western Australia]].<ref>{{Citation | author1=Western Australia. Metropolitan Region Planning Authority | author2=Hamer, M. E | author3=Western Australia. Town Planning Dept | title=Metropolitan region scheme report, 1962 | publication-date=1962 | publisher=Town Planning Dept | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/27706560 | accessdate=8 June 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Western Australia. Metropolitan Region Planning Authority | author2=Western Australia. Town Planning Department | title=Metropolitan region scheme map Perth Western Australia | publication-date=1963 | publisher=The Authority | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/21671013 | accessdate=8 June 2014 }}</ref> * 1970: MRPA adopted the [[Corridor Plan for Perth]]<ref>{{cite book | title = The corridor plan for Perth | author = Metropolitan Region Planning Authority | year = 1970 | oclc = 521177| isbn = 0-7309-5693-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planning.wa.gov.au/Publications/92.aspx |title=Commercial Land Use Survey 1997 |author=Ministry for Planning |accessdate=2007-07-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006120721/http://www.planning.wa.gov.au/Publications/92.aspx |archivedate=6 October 2007 }}</ref> * 1984: MRPA purchased the [[Piney Lakes Reserve]] and reserved it as a regional open space. The Reserve is owned in freehold by the WAPC and vested with the [[City of Melville]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pineylakes.org/piney_lakes_survey.htm | title = Piney Lakes Reserve: History and Environment | work = Piney Lakes | accessdate = 2007-07-17 }}</ref> * 1990: MPRA adopts [[Metroplan]]. * 2004: MPRA adopts [[Network City]]. * 2004: First regional interim development order gazetted by the WAPC to implement the Ningaloo Coast regional strategy. * 2008: Revised [[Residential Design Codes]] adopted. * 2011: MPRA adopts [[Directions 2031 and Beyond]].
